---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout title="California Road Data API">
	<article class="prose max-w-3xl mx-auto prose-slate">
		<h1>California Road Data API</h1>
		<p>
			California Road Data is the public, read-only API layer for current
			Caltrans road-condition data. It does not require an API key, account,
			or OAuth token.
		</p>

		<h2>Quick start</h2>
		<pre><code>GET /api/caltrans/{"{type}"}/{"{district}"}</code></pre>
		<p>
			For example, this returns the current Caltrans traffic-camera feed for
			District 4:
		</p>
		<pre><code>https://californiaroaddata.com/api/caltrans/cctv/04</code></pre>

		<h2>Parameters</h2>
		<ul>
			<li><code>type</code>: one of <code>cctv</code>, <code>cms</code>, <code>cc</code>, <code>lcs</code>, <code>rwis</code>, or <code>tt</code>.</li>
			<li><code>district</code>: a two-digit Caltrans district identifier, such as <code>04</code>.</li>
		</ul>
		<p>
			Not every source is available in every district. Use
			<a href="/api/metadata"> API metadata</a> to see the supported combinations.
		</p>

		<h2>Machine-readable resources</h2>
		<ul>
			<li><a href="/openapi.json">OpenAPI 3.1 description</a></li>
			<li><a href="/.well-known/api-catalog">RFC 9727 API catalog</a></li>
			<li><a href="/api/health">Service status</a></li>
		</ul>

		<h2>Data source and caching</h2>
		<p>
			Responses are derived from public Caltrans district feeds and may be cached
			briefly. Treat live conditions as time-sensitive and follow official traffic
			controls while traveling.
		</p>
	</article>
</Layout>
